not the best move. I think that the order of the moves in this opening is important.

according to the books that was not a good move. white should strike in the center at once and play 7. d4.
the continue may be 7... Nxb3 8. axb3 f6 9. c4 b4 10. Nh4 Ne7 11. Be3 g6 12. Qd2 exd4 13. Bxd4 Bg7 14. Be3 a5 15. Bh6 0-0 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qe3 with great advantage for white (Ernst - Agdestein, Gausdal, 1987)

first, I thought that the best move here was 11. dxe4 with an open d file that looks promising. 
than I realized that there is no place to put the bishop and the Knight in order to move the second rook to that file.
since that plan seems to take quite a while I'll agree that 11. d5 is the best move in that position.
maybe 11... Nf6 was a bit better in order to pin the rook to the e pawn.
white gains his space back and ruin black's pawn shield all at once.

what about 12... Qa5? there are few options afterwards:
1) 13. Nd2 Rb8 (13.... Nf6 14. Nc4! +-) 14. Nf1 Nf6 15. Bg5 0-0 with an equal position.
2) 13. axb5!! Qxa1 14. Bh6! Nxh6 15. Na3 Qxe1+ 16. Nxe1 0-0 17. b6 and despite the lack of material there is an advantage to white.

14. Qc4 must be considered.
14... Qb5 15. Na3 Qxc4 16. Nxc4 and white is better.
